 first comprehensive text on a key area of management practice , exploring what commissioning is, where it has come from and where it might be taking us. With a wide range of leading contributors from fields including health care, social care, local government , the book takes students, practitioners and managers through key stages of the commissioning cycle as well as addressing cross-cutting themes such as the economics of commissioning, user involvement and commissioning in an era of personalisation. It is essential reading for everyone involved in the planning and delivery of health and social care - for social policy students, health and social care practitioners, managers and policy makers alike.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aHealth planning. 0aHealth services administration. 0aSocial work administration. 7aMEDICAL / Health Policy.2bisacsh1 aAllen, Kerry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBovaird, Tony, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDickinson, Helen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDuffy, Simon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEllins, Jo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGlasby, Jon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGlasby, Jon, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHothersall, Eleanor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLonsdale, Chris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarshall, Tom, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNeedham, Catherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNicholds, Alyson, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabula